{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626694"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:40:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:40:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17091"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17091"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.09,0.85,0.06,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9781"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77715"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9781"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17091"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63230"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2994"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5295"},{"type":"tags","id":"10111"},{"type":"tags","id":"10122"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22959"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23185"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77715"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGlucocorticoids are commonly prescribed medications that can affect the endocrine system through multiple mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the effect of exogenous glucocorticoids on the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Has no effect on endogenous hormone production","Directly stimulates adrenal cortisol production","Suppresses both corticotropin-releasing hormone and adrenocorticotropic hormone production","Stimulates corticotropin-releasing hormone production","Increases adrenocorticotropic hormone production only"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EExogenous glucocorticoids cause \u003Cstrong\u003Esuppression of both corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH) and adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) production\u003C/strong\u003E through negative feedback mechanisms. This can lead to hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis suppression with long-term use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHas no effect on endogenous hormone production\u003C/strong\u003E - Exogenous glucocorticoids provide negative feedback to the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis, leading to suppression of endogenous hormone production\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly stimulates adrenal cortisol production\u003C/strong\u003E - Exogenous glucocorticoids suppress endogenous cortisol production by inhibiting ACTH release\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates corticotropin-releasing hormone production\u003C/strong\u003E - Glucocorticoids provide negative feedback to the hypothalamus, suppressing CRH production to reduce ACTH release\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases adrenocorticotropic hormone production only\u003C/strong\u003E - Glucocorticoids suppress ACTH production through both direct effects on the pituitary and indirect effects via reduced CRH\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this mechanism is crucial as sudden withdrawal of long-term glucocorticoid therapy can result in adrenal crisis due to impaired endogenous cortisol production.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Glucocorticoids exert negative feedback on the hypothalamus and anterior pituitary to suppress corticotropin-releasing hormone and adrenocorticotropic hormone production.","Long-term exogenous glucocorticoid therapy can cause hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis suppression.","Sudden withdrawal of glucocorticoids after long-term use can lead to adrenal crisis due to impaired endogenous cortisol production."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Gjerstad JK, Lightman SL, Spiga F. Role of glucocorticoid negative feedback in the regulation of HPA axis pulsatility. Stress. 2018;21(5):403-416. doi:10.1080/10253890.2018.1470238"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63230"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17091"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63230"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T00:02:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T00:02:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9781"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77715"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji